;{{Anchor|Abrasion}}Abrasion: A superficial wound in which the topmost layers of the skin are scraped off ;{{Anchor|ABCs}} ABCs: Airway, breathing and circulation ;{{Anchor|AED}}AED: Automated External Defibrillator ;{{Anchor|Airway}}Airway: The passages which transfer air from the outside environment to the lungs; the tracha, bronchi, bronchioles and alveoli ;{{Anchor|Artery}}Artery: A blood vessel carrying blood away from the heart; contains oxygen-rich, high-pressure blood in the systemic cardiorespiratory system ;{{Anchor|Avulsion}}Avulsion: A tearing away of a section of skin from the layers of tissue beneath it ;{{Anchor|Bystander}}Bystander: Any person, trained or untrained, who assists in an emergency situation, but not as part of a duty of employment ;{{Anchor|Capillary}}Capillary: The smallest blood vessels in the body; the skin is rife with capillaries ;{{Anchor|Carotid artery}}Carotid artery: The main artery providing blood supply to the head.[[Image:Gray507.png|thumb|The carotid artery is the largest artery shown here; click for a larger version.]] ;{{Anchor|Causation}}Causation: Determination of whether the defendant's actions are causally linked to any harm ;{{Anchor|Circulation}}Circulation: The movement of blood throughout the body; performed by the heart ;{{Anchor|Consciousness}}Consciousness (level of): A state of awareness or lack thereof ;{{Anchor|Consent}}Consent: A legal condition whereby a person can be said to have given consent based upon an appreciation and understanding of the facts and implications of an action ;{{Anchor|CPR}}CPR: Cardiopulmonary resuscitation ;{{Anchor|Cyanosis}}Cyanosis: The bluish coloration of the skin due to the presence of deoxygenated blood near the skin surface; occurs when the oxygen saturation of arterial blood falls below 85% ;{{Anchor|Defibrillation}}Defibrillation: Delivering a therapeutic dose of electrical energy to the affected heart with a device called a defibrillator ;Diabetes: a disease causing an inability to regulate the level of sugar (glucose) in the blood ;{{Anchor|Distal}}Distal: The point on a limb furthest from its point of attachment to the body ;{{Anchor|Duty of care}}Duty of care: A legal obligation imposed on an individual requiring that they exercise a reasonable standard of care while performing any acts that could foreseeably harm others ;{{Anchor|EMS}}EMS: Emergency Medical System or Emergency Medical Services ;{{Anchor|History}}History: One of the 3 parts of a secondary survey ;{{Anchor|Hypoxia}}Hypoxia: A condition in which insufficient oxygen reaches body tissue ;{{Anchor|Incision}}Incision: A clean cut caused by a sharp-edged object ;Insulin: a hormone that allows glucose to travel from the bloodstream into the cells ;{{Anchor|Laceration}}Laceration: Irregular wounds caused by a blunt impact to soft tissue which lies over hard tissue; tearing of skin ;{{Anchor|Landmark}}Landmark: The location of compressions; on the midline of the chest, even with the nipples ;{{Anchor|Liability}}Liability: A legal doctrine that makes a person responsible for the damage and loss caused by their acts and omissions regardless of culpability; the requirements to prove liability are a)a duty of care exists b)the standard of care was breached c)causation exists ;{{Anchor|Myocardial infarction}}Myocardial Infarction: Heart attack; bleeding or blockage cuts off blood flow to part of the heart muscle ;{{Anchor|Nailbed}}Nailbed: The tissue under the nail; pinching the nail and observing the blood return to the nailbed is a good test of circulation at that location ;{{Anchor|Oedema}}{{Anchor|Edema}}Oedema (Edema): Swelling in the lower legs and ankles. Oedema is caused by a fluid build-up in the body. ;{{Anchor|Proximal}}Proximal: The point on a limb closest to its point of attachment to the body ;{{Anchor|Puncture}}Puncture: A wound caused by an object puncturing the skin ;{{Anchor|Semi-prone}}{{Anchor|Recovery}}Semi-prone position: A position which keeps the tongue from obstructing the airway and allows any fluids to drain from the mouth ''(aka recovery position)'' ;{{Anchor|Standard of care}}Standard of Care: The degree of prudence and caution required of an individual who is under a duty of care; the requirements of the standard are closely dependent on circumstances ;{{Anchor|Tachycardia}}Tachycardia: A rapid pulse generally a pulse over 100 at rest ;{{Anchor|Vein}}Vein: A blood vessel that carries blood toward the heart; most veins carry low-oxygen blood
